  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are numerous international laws and conventions aimed at combating money laundering. These laws are designed to foster international cooperation and establish standards for national legislation. Here are some of the most important ones:\n\n**Key International Conventions and Organizations:**\n\n*   **United Nations Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988 Vienna Convention):** While primarily focused on drug trafficking, this convention was the first major international instrument to criminalize money laundering associated with drug-related crimes. It requires signatory states to criminalize the laundering of proceeds derived from drug trafficking and to cooperate in international investigations and prosecutions.\n\n*   **Financial Action Task Force on Money Laundering (FATF):** Although not a treaty, FATF is an inter-governmental body that sets international standards for combating money laundering, terrorist financing, and proliferation financing. FATF's 40 Recommendations are the cornerstone of the global AML/CFT (Anti-Money Laundering/Combating the Financing of Terrorism) framework. FATF evaluates countries' compliance with these recommendations and identifies jurisdictions with weak or non-existent AML/CFT systems. It publishes lists of high-risk jurisdictions.\n\n*   **Council of Europe Convention on Laundering, Search, Seizure and Confiscation of the Proceeds from Crime (1990 Strasbourg Convention):** This convention broadened the scope of money laundering offenses beyond drug-related crimes to include proceeds from a wider range of serious crimes. It also established mechanisms for international cooperation in the investigation, prosecution, and confiscation of illicit proceeds.\n\n*   **United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime (2000 Palermo Convention):** This convention requires states to criminalize the laundering of proceeds from a wide range of transnational organized crimes, including human trafficking, arms trafficking, and corruption. It also promotes international cooperation in preventing and combating these crimes.\n\n*   **International Monetary Fund (IMF) and World Bank:** These organizations play a role in combating money laundering by providing technical assistance to countries seeking to strengthen their AML/CFT regimes and by conducting assessments of countries' compliance with international standards.\n\n*   **European Union Directives:** The EU has issued several directives on money laundering, which set minimum standards for AML legislation within the EU member states. These directives have been progressively updated to address emerging threats and to strengthen the EU's AML framework. The Sixth Anti-Money Laundering Directive (6AMLD) is a key example.\n\n**Key Aspects of International Anti-Money Laundering Laws:**\n\n*   **Criminalization of Money Laundering:** Requiring countries to criminalize the act of concealing or disguising the proceeds of crime to make them appear legitimate. This typically includes a wide range of predicate offenses (the crimes that generate the illicit funds).\n\n*   **Customer Due Diligence (CDD):** Requiring financial institutions and other designated businesses to identify and verify the identities of their customers.\n\n*   **Record Keeping:** Requiring financial institutions to maintain records of customer transactions.\n\n*   **Reporting of Suspicious Transactions (STRs):** Requiring financial institutions and other designated businesses to report suspicious transactions to the relevant authorities (Financial Intelligence Units or FIUs).\n\n*   **International Cooperation:** Facilitating the exchange of information and cooperation between countries in the investigation and prosecution of money laundering offenses. This includes mutual legal assistance treaties (MLATs) and other mechanisms for cross-border cooperation.\n\n*   **Asset Forfeiture:** Allowing for the seizure and confiscation of assets derived from or used in money laundering activities.\n\n*   **Regulation of Financial Institutions and Designated Non-Financial Businesses and Professions (DNFBPs):** Expanding AML obligations beyond traditional banks to include casinos, real estate agents, lawyers, accountants, and other businesses that may be vulnerable to money laundering.\n\n**In Summary:**\n\nA complex and evolving web of international laws, conventions, and standards exists to combat money laundering. These efforts are designed to disrupt criminal activity, protect financial systems, and promote international security.  The FATF plays a central role in setting global standards and monitoring countries' compliance. Individual nations then implement these principles within their own legal systems.",
